"Gabriel K.M.A., Endlicher W.R.","Urban and rural mortality rates during heat waves in Berlin and Brandenburg, Germany",2011,"Environmental Pollution","159","8-9",,"2044","2050",,,10.1016/j.envpol.2011.01.016,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79958839611&partnerID=40&md5=7bfdd9821b13e73ba80bd7e3e481a234","Geography Department, Humboldt-Universität Zu Berlin, Unter den Linden 6, 10099 Berlin, Germany; Leibniz Institute of Freshwater Ecology and Inland Fisheries, Berlin, Germany","Gabriel, K.M.A., Geography Department, Humboldt-Universität Zu Berlin, Unter den Linden 6, 10099 Berlin, Germany, Leibniz Institute of Freshwater Ecology and Inland Fisheries, Berlin, Germany; Endlicher, W.R., Geography Department, Humboldt-Universität Zu Berlin, Unter den Linden 6, 10099 Berlin, Germany","In large cities such as Berlin, human mortality rates increase during intense heat waves. Analysis of relevant data from north-eastern Germany revealed that, during the heat waves that occurred between 1990 and 2006, health risks were higher for older people in both rural and urban areas, but that, during the two main heat waves within that 17-year period of time, the highest mortality rates were from the city of Berlin, and in particular from its most densely built-up districts. Adaptation measures will need to be developed, particularly within urban areas, in order to cope with the expected future intensification of heat waves due to global climate change. © 2011 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Adaptation measures; Heat waves; Human mortality rates; Thermal stress; Urban climate","Adaptation measures; Brandenburg; Germany; Global climate changes; Heat waves; Human mortality; Large cities; Mortality rate; Older People; Urban areas; Urban climates; Health risks; Climate change; adaptive management; climate change; climate effect; environmental stress; health impact; health risk; mortality; public health; rural area; urban area; urban climate; adult; article; climate 